06444nam a22008175i 9780292760646DE-B159720211027022714.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||211027t20212014txu    fo  d z      eng d  a97802927606467 a10.7560/7572572doi  a(DE-B1597)587647  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  atxucUS-TX 4aNA682.M63 -- S26 2014eb 7aARC0050802bisacsh04a724.600aSanctioning Modernism :bArchitecture and the Making of Postwar Identities /ced. by Vladimir Kulić, Monica Penick, Timothy Parker. 1aAustin : bUniversity of Texas Press, c[2021] 4c©2014  a1 online resource  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tForeword -- tPreface -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction. Writing History: Reflections on the Story of Midcentury Modern Architecture -- tPART I. MODERNISM AND THE STATE -- tIntroduction -- t1. Bucharest: Th e City Transfigured -- t2. The Scope of Socialist Modernism: Architecture and State Representation in Postwar Yugoslavia -- t3. Czechoslovakia’s Model Housing Developments: Modern Architecture for the Socialist Future -- t4. Sanctioning Modernism and Tradition: Italian Architecture, the Vernacular, and the State -- tPART II. MAKING RELIGION MODERN -- tIntroduction -- t5. Uncertainty and the Modern Church: Two Roman Catholic Cathedrals in Britain -- t6. “Humanly sublime tensions”: Luigi Moretti’s Chiesa del Concilio (1965–1970) -- t7. Modernism and the Concept of Reform: Liturgy and Liturgical Architecture -- tPART III: MODERNISM AND DOMESTICITY -- tIntroduction -- t8. “Technologically” Modern: Th e Prefabricated House and the Wartime Experience of Skidmore, Owings and Merrill -- t9. “Modern but not too modern”: House Beautiful and the American Style -- t10. House and Haunted Garden -- tFurther Reading -- tContributors -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aIn the decades following World War II, modern architecture spread around the globe alongside increased modernization, urbanization, and postwar reconstruction—and it eventually won widespread acceptance. But as the limitations of conventional conceptions of modernism became apparent, modern architecture has come under increasing criticism. In this collection of essays, experienced and emerging scholars take a fresh look at postwar modern architecture by asking what it meant to be “modern,” what role modern architecture played in constructing modern identities, and who sanctioned (or was sanctioned by) modernism in architecture. This volume presents focused case studies of modern architecture in three realms—political, religious, and domestic—that address our very essence as human beings. Several essays explore developments in Czechoslovakia, Romania, and Yugoslavia and document a modernist design culture that crossed political barriers, such as the Iron Curtain, more readily than previously imagined. Other essays investigate various efforts to reconcile the concerns of modernist architects with the traditions of the Roman Catholic Church and other Christian institutions. And a final group of essays looks at postwar homebuilding in the United States and demonstrates how malleable and contested the image of the American home was in the mid-twentieth century. These inquiries show the limits of canonical views of modern architecture and reveal instead how civic institutions, ecclesiastical traditions, individual consumers, and others sought to sanction the forms and ideas of modern architecture in the service of their respective claims or desires to be modern.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 27. Okt 2021) 0aArchitecture and society. 0aModern movement. 7aARCHITECTURE / History / Contemporary (1945-).2bisacsh1 aDoordan, Dennis P., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/